i## Haversine Formula		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWith the functions above ready, we can finally start implementing the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHaversine formula. I'm using this implementation from Stackoverflow as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia reference:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://stackoverflow.com/a/27943	URL:https://stackoverflow.com/a/27943	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Convert degree to radian		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    deg2rad = x: x * pi / 180;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Haversine formula, input a pair of latitudes/longitudes, output surface distance on Earth		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    haversine = lat1: lon1: lat2: lon2: let		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Treat the Earth as a sphere with radius of 6371km		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      radius = 6371000;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Radian of latitude difference		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      rad_lat = deg2rad ((1.0 * lat2) - (1.0 * lat1));		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Radian of longitude difference		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      rad_lon = deg2rad ((1.0 * lon2) - (1.0 * lon1));		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Calculate based on formula		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      a = (sin (rad_lat / 2)) * (sin (rad_lat / 2)) + (cos (deg2rad (1.0 * lat1))) * (cos (deg2rad (1.0 * lat2))) * (sin (rad_lon / 2)) * (sin (rad_lon / 2));		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      c = 2 * atan ((sqrt a) / (sqrt (1 - a)));		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      radius * c;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
